"# Chapter 2 — Grade 2: Place Value & Repeated Addition

## Opening: The Power of Position

### History & How It Developed

For thousands of years, people counted with their fingers, made notches on sticks, and moved pebbles on counting boards. The Romans wrote XVI for sixteen and MCMXC for 1990—beautiful, but adding and subtracting was hard work. Around the year 500, mathematicians in India made a discovery that changed everything: **the position of a digit could tell you its value**. A \"3\" could mean three, or thirty, or three hundred, depending on where it sat. By the year 800, this idea—called *place value*—had spread across the trade routes to the Middle East and eventually to Europe, where it replaced Roman numerals for everyday arithmetic. The key insight was simple but profound: you only need ten symbols (0 through 9) if you let their *place* do the work.

### Uses & Utility in the World

Place value is the reason you can add 347 + 285 on paper by lining up the columns. It's why cash registers know that two quarters make fifty cents, not two cents. It's how we read odometers, count money, measure ingredients, and tell time. Every price tag, every clock, every measuring cup relies on the idea that the *place* of a digit multiplies its value by ten. Without place value, modern commerce, science, and engineering would grind to a halt.

### What We'll Cover and Why

In this chapter, we'll explore numbers up to 1000 by breaking them into **hundreds, tens, and ones**. We'll add and subtract by thinking about these places. We'll count money (quarters, dimes, nickels, pennies) and time (hours and minutes). And we'll discover that **arrays**—grids of dots arranged in rows and columns—are a way to see *repeated addition* with our eyes. By the end, you'll draw a 5×4 grid of dots and count it by rows, watching addition happen on the canvas.

### Its Utility in the runtime's World

Motoi's world is a 4096×4096 grid of dots. Every position is a pair of numbers; every color is a number; every animation is a sequence of numbers ticking up. When she arranges dots into rows and columns, she's using place value and repeated addition to organize space. When she counts frames—60 per second—she's counting by tens and ones. The same structure that lets you count money lets her count pixels, and the same place-value thinking that helps you add 347 + 285 helps her navigate a canvas four thousand dots wide.

---

## Topic 1: Counting & Place Value to 1000

### History & the Idea

Once people agreed that the *place* of a digit mattered, they could write any number—no matter how large—with just ten symbols. The rightmost place is *ones*, the next place left is *tens* (because ten ones make a ten), and the next is *hundreds* (because ten tens make a hundred). A number like 247 is really *2 hundreds + 4 tens + 7 ones*. This breakdown is called *place value*, and it's the skeleton that holds all arithmetic together.

### What We'll Cover

We'll write numbers as hundreds + tens + ones, count up and down by tens and hundreds, and see those counts move on a number line.

---

### Example 1: Breaking a Number into Places

<!-- BUILD: Run this program; it prints the breakdown and renders a number line with a marker at 247. -->

```scheme
(define (place-value n)
  (let* ((hundreds (quotient n 100))
         (remainder (modulo n 100))
         (tens (quotient remainder 10))
         (ones (modulo remainder 10)))
    (list hundreds tens ones)))

(define num 247)
(define places (place-value num))
(display \"247 = \")
(display (car places))
(display \" hundreds + \")
(display (cadr places))
(display \" tens + \")
(display (caddr places))
(display \" ones\")
(newline)

;; Render on a number line from 0 to 300
(plot/line (list (list 0 0) (list 300 0))
           '((title \"Number Line to 300\")
             (x-label \"value\")
             (y-label \"\")
             (width 600)
             (height 100)))
```

[VISUAL: A horizontal number line from 0 to 300 with a marker or label at 247; printed output shows \"247 = 2 hundreds + 4 tens + 7 ones\".]

---

### Example 2: Counting by Tens

<!-- BUILD: Plot a number line; scatter points at 0, 10, 20, ..., 100 to show the tens. -->

```scheme
(define (count-by-tens limit)
  (let loop ((n 0) (acc '()))
    (if (> n limit)
        (reverse acc)
        (loop (+ n 10) (cons n acc)))))

(define tens (count-by-tens 100))
(display \"Counting by tens: \")
(display tens)
(newline)

;; Plot as scatter points on a number line
(define points (map (lambda (x) (list x 0)) tens))
(plot/scatter points
              '((title \"Counting by Tens to 100\")
                (x-label \"value\")
                (y-label \"\")
                (width 600)
                (height 100)))
```

[VISUAL: A scatter plot on a number line from 0 to 100 with dots at 0, 10, 20, 30, ..., 100.]

---

### Example 3: Counting by Hundreds

<!-- BUILD: Same idea; scatter points at 0, 100, 200, ..., 1000. -->

```scheme
(define (count-by-hundreds limit)
  (let loop ((n 0) (acc '()))
    (if (> n limit)
        (reverse acc)
        (loop (+ n 100) (cons n acc)))))

(define hundreds (count-by-hundreds 1000))
(display \"Counting by hundreds: \")
(display hundreds)
(newline)

(define points (map (lambda (x) (list x 0)) hundreds))
(plot/scatter points
              '((title \"Counting by Hundreds to 1000\")
                (x-label \"value\")
                (y-label \"\")
                (width 800)
                (height 100)))
```

[VISUAL: A number line from 0 to 1000 with markers at every hundred: 0, 100, 200, ..., 1000.]

---

### Example 4: Building Numbers from Places

<!-- BUILD: Let the operator supply hundreds/tens/ones, build the number, print it, plot a bar showing the breakdown. -->

```scheme
(define (build-number hundreds tens ones)
  (+ (* hundreds 100)
     (* tens 10)
     ones))

(define h 3)
(define t 4)
(define o 7)
(define num (build-number h t o))

(display h)
(display \" hundreds + \")
(display t)
(display \" tens + \")
(display o)
(display \" ones = \")
(display num)
(newline)

;; Plot a stacked bar: hundreds in one color, tens in another, ones in a third
(define bar-data (list (list \"hundreds\" (* h 100))
                       (list \"tens\" (* t 10))
                       (list \"ones\" o)))
(plot/bar bar-data
          '((title \"Place Value of 347\")
            (x-label \"place\")
            (y-label \"value\")
            (width 400)
            (height 300)))
```

[VISUAL: A bar chart with three bars labeled \"hundreds\" (height 300), \"tens\" (height 40), \"ones\" (height 7), showing the additive breakdown of 347.]

---

### Example 5: Comparing Numbers by Place

<!-- BUILD: Compare 456 and 462 digit by digit, print which is larger, plot both on a number line. -->

```scheme
(define (place-value n)
  (let* ((h (quotient n 100))
         (r (modulo n 100))
         (t (quotient r 10))
         (o (modulo r 10)))
    (list h t o)))

(define a 456)
(define b 462)
(define pa (place-value a))
(define pb (place-value b))

(display a)
(display \" = \")
(display pa)
(display \" vs \")
(display b)
(display \" = \")
(display pb)
(newline)

(if (< a b)
    (display \"456 < 462 (same hundreds, same tens, but 6 ones < 2 ones is false; actually 456 < 462 because tens differ)\")
    (display \"456 >= 462\"))
(newline)

;; Plot both on a number line
(plot/scatter (list (list a 0) (list b 1))
              '((title \"456 vs 462 on the Number Line\")
                (x-label \"value\")
                (y-label \"\")
                (width 600)
                (height 100)))
```

[VISUAL: Two points on a number line near 450-470, showing 456 and 462 close together, with 462 slightly to the right.]

