## Topic 4: Money (Quarters, Dimes, Nickels, Pennies)

### History & How It Developed

Coins have been used for trade for over 2,500 years. The ancient Greeks and Romans minted silver and gold coins of different sizes; the bigger the coin, the more it was worth. In the United States, the dollar is divided into 100 cents, and we have coins worth 25 cents (a quarter), 10 cents (a dime), 5 cents (a nickel), and 1 cent (a penny). Counting money is an exercise in place value—except instead of tens, we count by 25s, 10s, 5s, and 1s.

### Uses & Utility in the World

Every time you buy something, you count money. You add up the cost of items, subtract what you pay from what you have, and calculate change. Cash registers do this automatically, but the math inside is the same as what you do on paper.

### What We'll Cover

We'll write programs that count collections of coins, add them up to dollar amounts, and make change.

### Utility in the runtime's World

The runtime might not carry coins, but she tracks resources—pixels, frames, memory. Counting by 25s and 10s is the same skill as counting by any other unit, and it teaches her to convert between different scales (100 pennies = 1 dollar, 60 frames = 1 second).

---

### Example 16: Counting Pennies, Nickels, Dimes, Quarters

<!-- BUILD: Given counts of each coin, compute the total value in cents, print it. -->

```scheme
(define (coin-value quarters dimes nickels pennies)
  (+ (* quarters 25)
     (* dimes 10)
     (* nickels 5)
     pennies))

(define q 3)
(define d 2)
(define n 4)
(define p 7)
(define total (coin-value q d n p))

(display q)
(display \" quarters + \")
(display d)
(display \" dimes + \")
(display n)
(display \" nickels + \")
(display p)
(display \" pennies = \")
(display total)
(display \" cents\")
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: A printed line showing \"3 quarters + 2 dimes + 4 nickels + 7 pennies = 112 cents\"; optionally a bar chart with four bars for quarters/dimes/nickels/pennies showing their contribution to the total.]

---

### Example 17: Converting Cents to Dollars and Cents

<!-- BUILD: Given 112 cents, print \"1 dollar and 12 cents\". -->

```scheme
(define cents 112)
(define dollars (quotient cents 100))
(define remaining (modulo cents 100))

(display cents)
(display \" cents = \")
(display dollars)
(display \" dollar and \")
(display remaining)
(display \" cents\")
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output \"112 cents = 1 dollar and 12 cents\".]

---

### Example 18: Making Change

<!-- BUILD: An item costs 67 cents; you pay with a dollar (100 cents); compute change. -->

```scheme
(define cost 67)
(define paid 100)
(define change (- paid cost))

(display \"Item costs \")
(display cost)
(display \" cents. You pay \")
(display paid)
(display \" cents. Change: \")
(display change)
(display \" cents.\")
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output showing the subtraction: \"Item costs 67 cents. You pay 100 cents. Change: 33 cents.\"]

---

### Example 19: Fewest Coins for Change

<!-- BUILD: Given 33 cents change, break it into quarters/dimes/nickels/pennies using the fewest coins. -->

```scheme
(define (make-change cents)
  (let* ((q (quotient cents 25))
         (r1 (modulo cents 25))
         (d (quotient r1 10))
         (r2 (modulo r1 10))
         (n (quotient r2 5))
         (p (modulo r2 5)))
    (list q d n p)))

(define change 33)
(define coins (make-change change))
(display change)
(display \" cents = \")
(display (car coins))
(display \" quarter, \")
(display (cadr coins))
(display \" dime, \")
(display (caddr coins))
(display \" nickel, \")
(display (cadddr coins))
(display \" pennies\")
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output \"33 cents = 1 quarter, 0 dime, 1 nickel, 3 pennies\"; optionally a bar chart showing the coin breakdown.]

---

### Example 20: Adding Two Amounts of Money

<!-- BUILD: Add $1.25 + $0.87 by converting to cents, adding, converting back. -->

```scheme
(define (dollars-to-cents d c)
  (+ (* d 100) c))

(define (cents-to-dollars total)
  (list (quotient total 100) (modulo total 100)))

(define amount1 (dollars-to-cents 1 25))  ; $1.25 = 125 cents
(define amount2 (dollars-to-cents 0 87))  ; $0.87 = 87 cents
(define sum (+ amount1 amount2))
(define result (cents-to-dollars sum))

(display \"$1.25 + $0.87 = $\")
(display (car result))
(display \".\")
(display (cadr result))
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output \"$1.25 + $0.87 = $2.12\".]

