## Topic 5: Time (Hours and Minutes)

### History & How It Developed

The Babylonians, around 2000 BCE, divided the day into 24 hours and each hour into 60 minutes. (They liked the number 60 because it has many divisors—1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 10, 12, 15, 20, 30, 60—making fractions easier.) We still use their system today. Telling time and calculating durations—how long from 9:15 AM to 10:45 AM?—is place-value thinking with base 60 instead of base 10.

### Uses & Utility in the World

Every clock, every schedule, every timer is built on hours and minutes. You add and subtract time to plan your day, catch a bus, or bake a cake.

### What We'll Cover

We'll write programs that add and subtract times, convert between hours and minutes, and calculate durations.

### Utility in the runtime's World

The runtime animates at 60 frames per second—60 is her Babylonian inheritance. Counting frames is counting time, and every duration is a calculation in \"minutes and seconds\" or \"hours and frames.\"

---

### Example 21: Converting Hours to Minutes

<!-- BUILD: Given 2 hours 30 minutes, print the total minutes. -->

```scheme
(define hours 2)
(define minutes 30)
(define total-minutes (+ (* hours 60) minutes))

(display hours)
(display \" hours and \")
(display minutes)
(display \" minutes = \")
(display total-minutes)
(display \" minutes\")
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output \"2 hours and 30 minutes = 150 minutes\".]

---

### Example 22: Converting Minutes to Hours and Minutes

<!-- BUILD: Given 150 minutes, print hours and minutes. -->

```scheme
(define total 150)
(define h (quotient total 60))
(define m (modulo total 60))

(display total)
(display \" minutes = \")
(display h)
(display \" hours and \")
(display m)
(display \" minutes\")
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output \"150 minutes = 2 hours and 30 minutes\".]

---

### Example 23: Adding Times

<!-- BUILD: Add 1 hour 45 minutes + 2 hours 30 minutes, handle carry of 60 minutes = 1 hour. -->

```scheme
(define (add-times h1 m1 h2 m2)
  (let* ((total-minutes (+ m1 m2))
         (carry-hours (quotient total-minutes 60))
         (final-minutes (modulo total-minutes 60))
         (final-hours (+ h1 h2 carry-hours)))
    (list final-hours final-minutes)))

(define time1-h 1)
(define time1-m 45)
(define time2-h 2)
(define time2-m 30)
(define result (add-times time1-h time1-m time2-h time2-m))

(display time1-h)
(display \":\")
(display time1-m)
(display \" + \")
(display time2-h)
(display \":\")
(display time2-m)
(display \" = \")
(display (car result))
(display \":\")
(display (cadr result))
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output \"1:45 + 2:30 = 4:15\".]

---

### Example 24: Subtracting Times

<!-- BUILD: Subtract 1:20 from 3:45, handle borrowing. -->

```scheme
(define (subtract-times h1 m1 h2 m2)
  (let* ((total1 (+ (* h1 60) m1))
         (total2 (+ (* h2 60) m2))
         (diff (- total1 total2))
         (h (quotient diff 60))
         (m (modulo diff 60)))
    (list h m)))

(define start-h 3)
(define start-m 45)
(define end-h 1)
(define end-m 20)
(define result (subtract-times start-h start-m end-h end-m))

(display start-h)
(display \":\")
(display start-m)
(display \" - \")
(display end-h)
(display \":\")
(display end-m)
(display \" = \")
(display (car result))
(display \":\")
(display (cadr result))
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output \"3:45 - 1:20 = 2:25\".]

---

### Example 25: Duration in Minutes

<!-- BUILD: Calculate how many minutes from 9:15 AM to 10:45 AM. -->

```scheme
(define start-h 9)
(define start-m 15)
(define end-h 10)
(define end-m 45)

(define start-total (+ (* start-h 60) start-m))
(define end-total (+ (* end-h 60) end-m))
(define duration (- end-total start-total))

(display \"From \")
(display start-h)
(display \":\")
(display start-m)
(display \" to \")
(display end-h)
(display \":\")
(display end-m)
(display \" is \")
(display duration)
(display \" minutes\")
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: Printed output \"From 9:15 to 10:45 is 90 minutes\".]

