## Topic 6: Arrays as Repeated Addition

### History & How It Developed

Ancient farmers planted seeds in rows and columns—5 rows of 4 plants each—and needed to know the total. Instead of counting one by one, they learned to *multiply*: 5 rows × 4 plants = 20 plants. But multiplication is really **repeated addition**: 4 + 4 + 4 + 4 + 4 = 20. An array—a grid of objects arranged in rows and columns—is a way to *see* this repeated addition with your eyes. By the time the Greeks were building the Parthenon (around 400 BCE), architects used arrays to count columns and tiles. Arrays are the bridge from addition to multiplication.

### Uses & Utility in the World

Every spreadsheet is an array. Every chessboard, every egg carton, every city grid of streets and avenues. When you set a table for 6 people with 4 utensils each, you're thinking in arrays. When you buy a case of 12 bottles × 6 packs, you're counting an array.

### What We'll Cover

We'll draw arrays on the canvas—grids of dots—and count them by adding up the rows. We'll see that 5 rows of 4 dots is the same as adding 4 five times. We'll build up to the summit artifact: a 5×4 array that we count by rows.

### Utility in the runtime's World

the runtime's entire world is an array—4096 columns × 4096 rows of pixels. Every sprite, every tile, every grid she draws is an array. Counting arrays teaches her to navigate the canvas and understand that *area* is rows times columns, which is the foundation of all her drawing.

---

### Example 26: A 3×2 Array (Three Rows of Two Dots Each)

<!-- BUILD: Draw 3 rows of 2 dots each, spaced evenly on the canvas; print \"3 rows of 2 = 2+2+2 = 6\". -->

```scheme
(define rows 3)
(define cols 2)
(define total (+ cols cols cols))

(display rows)
(display \" rows of \")
(display cols)
(display \" = \")
(display cols)
(display \"+\")
(display cols)
(display \"+\")
(display cols)
(display \" = \")
(display total)
(newline)

;; Render as a grid: x = col * 20, y = row * 20, each dot is a point
(define (make-grid r c)
  (let loop-r ((row 0) (acc '()))
    (if (>= row r)
        acc
        (let loop-c ((col 0) (acc2 acc))
          (if (>= col c)
              (loop-r (+ row 1) acc2)
              (loop-c (+ col 1) (cons (list (* col 20) (* row 20)) acc2)))))))

(define points (make-grid rows cols))
(plot/scatter points
              '((title \"3×2 Array (3 rows of 2)\")
                (x-label \"column\")
                (y-label \"row\")
                (width 100)
                (height 100)))
```

[VISUAL: A 3×2 grid of dots on the canvas, evenly spaced; printed output \"3 rows of 2 = 2+2+2 = 6\".]

